00:00:57.180 --> 00:00:58.300
- As you know from the program

00:00:58.300 --> 00:01:00.460
and just from general knowledge,

00:01:00.460 --> 00:01:03.720
these lectures were established in 1976

00:01:03.720 --> 00:01:06.030
by colleagues, joined by friends, family,

00:01:06.030 --> 00:01:08.900
and students to commemorate
the contributions

00:01:08.900 --> 00:01:12.140
and their continuing
influences and transformations

00:01:12.140 --> 00:01:13.440
of Carl Sauer,

00:01:13.440 --> 00:01:15.590
who was perhaps one of the, or certainly,

00:01:15.590 --> 00:01:18.050
is one of the most influential geographers

00:01:18.050 --> 00:01:20.610
of the 20th century.

00:01:20.610 --> 00:01:23.800
His books, his works,
are veritably crossed

00:01:23.800 --> 00:01:25.160
and trans-disciplinary,

00:01:25.160 --> 00:01:26.849
there are many concepts and approaches

00:01:26.849 --> 00:01:29.390
that Sauer pioneered and/or championed

00:01:29.390 --> 00:01:31.070
that scholars use today,

00:01:31.070 --> 00:01:34.930
often without realizing their
origin and their history.

00:01:34.930 --> 00:01:36.650
Sauer was a professor of geography

00:01:36.650 --> 00:01:40.770
here at Berkeley from 1923 to 1957.

00:01:40.770 --> 00:01:42.460
And he was an emeritus professor

00:01:42.460 --> 00:01:45.220
until his death in 1975.

00:01:45.220 --> 00:01:47.240
This was the formative time

00:01:47.240 --> 00:01:50.860
of what became a distinctly
Berkeley cultural geography.

00:01:50.860 --> 00:01:52.590
And you would not be surprised to learn

00:01:52.590 --> 00:01:54.430
that being a contemporary here,

00:01:54.430 --> 00:01:56.840
with the anthropologist Alfred Kroeber,

00:01:56.840 --> 00:01:58.190
there were discussions and debates

00:01:58.190 --> 00:01:59.550
between the two and their students,

00:01:59.550 --> 00:02:02.520
both leaving a legacy of
promise and challenges

00:02:02.520 --> 00:02:04.930
to the understanding of human cultures,

00:02:04.930 --> 00:02:07.180
their landscapes, and their histories.

00:02:09.120 --> 00:02:11.600
We are honored that
members of the Sauer family

00:02:11.600 --> 00:02:12.750
are here with us today for

00:02:12.750 --> 00:02:14.740
the 21st Sauer Memorial Lecture,

00:02:14.740 --> 00:02:15.778
and we are grateful to them

00:02:15.778 --> 00:02:18.700
for their continuing
support of the endowment.

00:02:19.570 --> 00:02:22.330
Today I am really pleased to introduce

00:02:22.330 --> 00:02:25.030
our 21st Sauer Lecturer,
Professor Marie Price,

00:02:25.030 --> 00:02:27.060
of the George Washington University,

00:02:27.060 --> 00:02:30.200
where she is recently Chair of
the Department of Geography.

00:02:30.200 --> 00:02:32.250
As you will understand from her lecture,

00:02:32.250 --> 00:02:34.810
she is also a professor
of international affairs

00:02:34.810 --> 00:02:36.500
and has served as director

00:02:36.500 --> 00:02:37.830
of the Latin American Studies

00:02:37.830 --> 00:02:41.570
for the Elliot School of
International Affairs.

00:02:41.570 --> 00:02:44.650
She is frequently on call for the press

00:02:44.650 --> 00:02:47.750
and many organizations,
and if you go onto Google,

00:02:47.750 --> 00:02:50.590
you can find some interviews with her.

00:02:50.590 --> 00:02:53.240
Given her expertise on such crucial topics

00:02:53.240 --> 00:02:55.920
for today's world as immigration,

00:02:55.920 --> 00:02:57.450
this is something of a homecoming,

00:02:57.450 --> 00:02:58.460
if you will, for Marie.

00:02:58.460 --> 00:02:59.760
She is a Californian.

00:02:59.760 --> 00:03:01.720
She is a Berkeley graduate.

00:03:01.720 --> 00:03:03.710
Having earned her bachelor's degree here

00:03:03.710 --> 00:03:05.780
in the Department of Geography before

00:03:05.780 --> 00:03:08.110
attending Syracuse University from where

00:03:08.110 --> 00:03:12.560
she received her PhD in 1991.

00:03:12.560 --> 00:03:14.380
She's had extensive field experience

00:03:14.380 --> 00:03:16.390
researching urban immigration,

00:03:16.390 --> 00:03:19.310
migration, and development
in Latin America.

00:03:19.310 --> 00:03:21.920
She's surveyed immigration from Bolivia,

00:03:21.920 --> 00:03:25.650
investigated migration and
coffee cultivation in Venezuela,

00:03:25.650 --> 00:03:27.840
and gathered data and
conducted field research

00:03:27.840 --> 00:03:29.990
on global cities and immigrants.

00:03:29.990 --> 00:03:31.480
Her articles have been published

00:03:31.480 --> 00:03:33.310
in such journals as the Annals of

00:03:33.310 --> 00:03:35.830
the Association of the
American Geographers,

00:03:35.830 --> 00:03:37.320
the Geographical Review,

00:03:37.320 --> 00:03:40.310
the Journal of Historical
Geography, Urban Geography,

00:03:40.310 --> 00:03:42.830
International Journal of
Urban and Regional Research,

00:03:42.830 --> 00:03:46.340
Studies in Comparative
International Development and Focus.

00:03:46.340 --> 00:03:49.240
Her books include a co-edited book,

00:03:49.240 --> 00:03:50.970
Migrants to the Metropolis:

00:03:50.970 --> 00:03:53.950
the Rise of Immigrant
Gateway Cities in 2008,

00:03:53.950 --> 00:03:55.550
with Lisa Benton-Short,

00:03:55.550 --> 00:03:59.350
and up now to the 5th
edition of the textbook,

00:03:59.350 --> 00:04:01.300
Diversity Amid Globalization:

00:04:01.300 --> 00:04:03.390
World Regions, Environment,
and Development,

00:04:03.390 --> 00:04:06.860
co-authored with Les
Rowntree, Martin Lewis,

00:04:06.860 --> 00:04:08.980
and William Wyckoff,
who are all here today

00:04:08.980 --> 00:04:10.730
to celebrate their co-author.

00:04:12.830 --> 00:04:15.080
Price is a member and very active member

00:04:15.080 --> 00:04:17.990
of several of the key
professional associations,

00:04:17.990 --> 00:04:20.900
including the American
Geographical Society,

00:04:20.900 --> 00:04:22.890
the Association of American Geographers,

00:04:22.890 --> 00:04:25.470
the Institute of Current World Affairs,

00:04:25.470 --> 00:04:27.690
the Latin American Studies Association,

00:04:27.690 --> 00:04:30.070
and the Society of Women Geographers.

00:04:30.070 --> 00:04:31.810
She's been awarded numerous honors

00:04:31.810 --> 00:04:33.980
for her extensive work in the field.

00:04:33.980 --> 00:04:38.320
In 2010, the Conference of
Latin Americanist Geographers

00:04:38.320 --> 00:04:40.120
awarded her the Preston E. James

00:04:40.120 --> 00:04:42.650
Eminent Latin Americanist career award.

00:04:42.650 --> 00:04:45.760
She received the 2005 Trachtenberg Prize

00:04:45.760 --> 00:04:49.100
for Teaching from GW, George
Washington University,

00:04:49.100 --> 00:04:52.250
and her article that she
co-authored with Catherine Cooper:

00:04:52.250 --> 00:04:54.310
Competing Visions, Shifting Boundaries:

00:04:54.310 --> 00:04:57.360
The Construction of Latin
America as a World Region

00:04:57.360 --> 00:05:00.830
was honored as a best current,
concant article of 2008

00:05:00.830 --> 00:05:02.290
in the Journal of Geography

00:05:02.290 --> 00:05:05.610
by the National Council
for Geographic Education.

00:05:05.610 --> 00:05:07.830
We are therefore more than pleased

00:05:07.830 --> 00:05:11.400
to be able to welcome
Marie back to Berkeley,

00:05:11.400 --> 00:05:13.950
where she will give
her presentation today.

00:05:13.950 --> 00:05:15.130
As you can see,

00:05:15.130 --> 00:05:17.750
Diffusion, Deflection, and Diversity:

00:05:17.750 --> 00:05:21.630
A geographic perspective on
contemporary immigration.

00:05:21.630 --> 00:05:22.675
Marie.

00:05:22.675 --> 00:05:25.675
