time for some questions

00:51:46.860 --> 00:51:47.830
if anybody would like

00:51:47.830 --> 00:51:50.210
and we do have a
microphone to pass around.

00:51:50.210 --> 00:51:52.030
Anybody wanna ask any questions

00:51:52.030 --> 00:51:53.580
or make some comments?

00:51:53.580 --> 00:51:54.660
- [Audience Member 1] Great talk, Marie.

00:51:54.660 --> 00:51:57.680
I'm wondering with
communities that do aggregate,

00:51:57.680 --> 00:51:59.700
if you find another level of aggregation

00:51:59.700 --> 00:52:02.580
based on region or ethnicity, for example,

00:52:02.580 --> 00:52:05.133
do the Bolivians who are
native Quechuan speakers

00:52:05.133 --> 00:52:07.290
tend to live somewhere different from

00:52:07.290 --> 00:52:09.340
those who are Spanish or Aymara speakers?

00:52:13.530 --> 00:52:15.130
- [Marie] The linguistic isolation's

00:52:15.130 --> 00:52:17.830
a really interesting one and you can find,

00:52:17.830 --> 00:52:20.070
but in general, I find no,

00:52:20.070 --> 00:52:21.710
that actually most of
the speakers who come

00:52:21.710 --> 00:52:24.450
are either Spanish or Quechuan speakers

00:52:24.450 --> 00:52:26.370
and we don't have many Aymara speakers.

00:52:26.370 --> 00:52:28.260
But I mean, if you start
looking at language

00:52:28.260 --> 00:52:32.430
and some of the ACS data,
you can tease that out,

00:52:32.430 --> 00:52:36.370
but what I've found, the
separation in Bolivians,

00:52:36.370 --> 00:52:37.950
and I've mapped this quite a bit,

00:52:37.950 --> 00:52:41.830
