00:52:53.510 --> 00:52:57.810
But you could definitely
move down in scale

00:52:57.810 --> 00:52:59.580
in terms of region of origin, language,

00:52:59.580 --> 00:53:02.450
and really come up with some
different patterns, I'm sure.

00:53:02.450 --> 00:53:04.090
Especially for the Indians,

00:53:04.090 --> 00:53:06.360
and I'm still waiting to dig into that.

00:53:08.110 --> 00:53:08.943
- [Audience Member 2] I'm curious, Marie,

00:53:08.943 --> 00:53:12.060
how important is religious affiliation,

00:53:12.060 --> 00:53:13.940
particularly for sort of evangelic

00:53:13.940 --> 00:53:15.630
or fundamentalist communities?

00:53:17.170 --> 00:53:19.510
- [Marie] You know, I
haven't looked at religion

00:53:19.510 --> 00:53:22.460
and I should, but certainly,

00:53:24.230 --> 00:53:27.330
Central Americans are
very strongly evangelical

00:53:27.330 --> 00:53:29.450
and they often form their own churches

00:53:29.450 --> 00:53:32.460
and have very clear transnational linkages

00:53:32.460 --> 00:53:35.070
and direct flow so on one level,

00:53:35.070 --> 00:53:36.660
you can look at the Catholic Church,

00:53:36.660 --> 00:53:41.660
which probably has benefited
enormously from immigration.

00:53:41.960 --> 00:53:46.470
Especially Latino, Filipino,
Vietnamese Catholics.

00:53:47.890 --> 00:53:51.700
And that is, but there's also,

00:53:51.700 --> 00:53:53.530
my colleague Elizabeth
Chaco's worked a lot

00:53:53.530 --> 00:53:56.060
on Ethiopians, there's
the Coptic Christians,

00:53:56.060 --> 00:53:59.440
and they form their own churches, and so,

00:53:59.440 --> 00:54:03.150
while country of origin
is a convenient start

00:54:03.150 --> 00:54:06.360
for diversity, you can
slice and dice at religion.

00:54:06.360 --> 00:54:10.730
There's a group that have
tried to look at religious

00:54:10.730 --> 00:54:15.155
mapping and where churches
are, and synagogues and temples

00:54:15.155 --> 00:54:17.750
as a way to understand the complexity.

00:54:17.750 --> 00:54:19.980
The thing that always
amazes me in Washington

00:54:19.980 --> 00:54:21.830
because we have a large Korean population,

00:54:21.830 --> 00:54:24.300
we had huge Korean churches,

00:54:24.300 --> 00:54:25.750
and they are very well attended,

00:54:25.750 --> 00:54:28.880
so I think like, to get
at the Korean Baptists,

00:54:28.880 --> 00:54:31.010
in particular, that's really powerful.

00:54:31.960 --> 00:54:34.740
Bolivians, my feeling and experience is,

00:54:34.740 --> 00:54:36.020
they don't go to church so much.

00:54:36.020 --> 00:54:37.347
They like soccer better.

00:54:37.347 --> 00:54:38.180
(audience laughs)

00:54:38.180 --> 00:54:40.370
So soccer was clearly the place to go

00:54:40.370 --> 00:54:41.780
to learn what was going on.

00:54:44.306 --> 00:54:45.180
There's a couple hands back there.

00:54:46.304 --> 00:54:47.290
- [Audience Member 3]
Yes thank you. Pardon me.

00:54:47.290 --> 00:54:48.910
Thank you very much.

00:54:48.910 --> 00:54:52.010
Some time ago, I found a old study,

00:54:52.010 --> 00:54:54.880
that I guess now at the
time was quite well known,

00:54:54.880 --> 00:54:56.810
was really a confluence study

00:54:56.810 --> 00:54:58.830
of the working class communities,

00:54:58.830 --> 00:54:59.663
which is a sociological,

00:54:59.663 --> 00:55:02.720
rather than anthropological,
or geographical,

00:55:02.720 --> 00:55:05.910
at least not self-consciously
either of those.

00:55:05.910 --> 00:55:10.300
And he, this was Chicago in the 50s,

00:55:10.300 --> 00:55:11.830
so we're talking about all the residue

00:55:11.830 --> 00:55:14.630
of Eastern Europeans or Southern Europeans

00:55:14.630 --> 00:55:17.240
who are still Eastern European
and Southern European.

00:55:17.240 --> 00:55:19.970
And one of the interesting things was,

00:55:19.970 --> 00:55:24.850
this was a time of industrial prosperity.

00:55:24.850 --> 00:55:27.200
The steel mills were rolling along,

00:55:27.200 --> 00:55:29.342
I don't know the exact ups and downs,

00:55:29.342 --> 00:55:31.150
economically at the time,

00:55:31.150 --> 00:55:34.390
but one of the key places of negotiation

00:55:34.390 --> 00:55:36.800
between the different
groups was the workplace,

00:55:36.800 --> 00:55:39.560
and sort of large industrial places

00:55:39.560 --> 00:55:43.380
with a lot of internal
technical division of labor.

00:55:43.380 --> 00:55:45.280
So there's all these fights about

00:55:45.280 --> 00:55:46.190
who's going to be the foreman

00:55:46.190 --> 00:55:48.140
and who's going to work under whom,

00:55:48.140 --> 00:55:50.530
and they, according to Kornblume's

