Orthodoxy and Catholicity,

00:56:09.010 --> 00:56:10.460
that is also another place

00:56:10.460 --> 00:56:12.210
because there's only so many churches

00:56:12.210 --> 00:56:14.340
and you've gotta sort of, once again,

00:56:14.340 --> 00:56:15.280
negotiate it in the church.

00:56:15.280 --> 00:56:16.569
So I was wondering about,

00:56:16.569 --> 00:56:19.740
you know I keep hearing
that in your presentation,

00:56:19.740 --> 00:56:22.800
we looked at a lot of residential areas,

00:56:22.800 --> 00:56:26.044
and I think in the suburbs
they don't mix it up too much,

00:56:26.044 --> 00:56:30.710
but I wanted to know more
about that. Thank you.

00:56:30.710 --> 00:56:32.810
- [Marie] Well, two responses.

00:56:32.810 --> 00:56:34.300
One of the curious things is,

00:56:34.300 --> 00:56:36.560
in the near-in suburbs and the cities,

00:56:36.560 --> 00:56:39.560
a lot of churches,
different congregations,

00:56:39.560 --> 00:56:42.384
have really lost their,

00:56:42.384 --> 00:56:45.220
the base of their congregations.

00:56:45.220 --> 00:56:46.770
So what often happens is that

00:56:46.770 --> 00:56:49.620
the churches in a sense rent out space,

00:56:49.620 --> 00:56:52.850
or appeal to a diversity of immigrants,

00:56:52.850 --> 00:56:55.330
and so you might have a congregation

00:56:55.330 --> 00:56:57.450
that offers religious services

00:56:57.450 --> 00:56:58.860
in seven or eight languages

00:56:58.860 --> 00:57:00.420
and the different groups come in.

00:57:00.420 --> 00:57:03.480
And so you can have groups
sharing the same space

00:57:03.480 --> 00:57:05.270
but coming in at different times.

00:57:05.270 --> 00:57:10.270
So how integrative it
is is not, it's limited.

00:57:10.300 --> 00:57:11.970
In terms of employment,

00:57:13.050 --> 00:57:16.270
some work I've looked at
immigrant entrepreneurship,

00:57:16.270 --> 00:57:18.450
in general, immigrants are more likely

00:57:18.450 --> 00:57:22.340
to be self-employed than the native-born.

00:57:22.340 --> 00:57:24.400
And there's reasons for that,

00:57:24.400 --> 00:57:26.040
you know being excluded from the workforce

00:57:26.040 --> 00:57:28.300
in some ways and also maybe a desire

00:57:28.300 --> 00:57:29.750
to create your own business.

00:57:30.600 --> 00:57:33.210
But in the case of Bolivians,

00:57:33.210 --> 00:57:34.500
where I've just written a piece

00:57:34.500 --> 00:57:36.114
on immigrant entrepreneurship
in Washington,

00:57:36.114 --> 00:57:39.380
they had twice a rate of entrepreneurship

00:57:39.380 --> 00:57:42.040
than other Hispanics in the area,

00:57:42.040 --> 00:57:44.700
and they're really good
at opening a business.

00:57:44.700 --> 00:57:46.130
Say, we're gonna do drywall.

00:57:46.130 --> 00:57:48.221
Now drywall's not a lot of fun.

00:57:48.221 --> 00:57:49.054
(audience laughs)

00:57:49.054 --> 00:57:49.887
I don't know if any of
you have done drywall,

00:57:49.887 --> 00:57:51.120
they're heavy sheets.

00:57:51.120 --> 00:57:53.150
But then they just bring in a stream

00:57:53.150 --> 00:57:55.030
of young guys from the country.

00:57:55.030 --> 00:57:56.956
There's a boss that organizes it,

00:57:56.956 --> 00:57:59.230
there's a lot of trust,

00:57:59.230 --> 00:58:02.410
maybe some self-exploitation
amongst co-ethnics,

00:58:02.410 --> 00:58:05.270
and they get their drywall
business up and running.

00:58:06.600 --> 00:58:08.124
Women have really cornered the market

00:58:08.124 --> 00:58:13.124
in these very, kind of
cutesy, domestic services.

00:58:13.730 --> 00:58:16.020
One, it's got about 45 Bolivian women,

00:58:16.020 --> 00:58:20.170
called Maid in America, M-A-I-D.

00:58:21.720 --> 00:58:22.860
Makes me smile.

00:58:22.860 --> 00:58:26.010
So they run around in
little Toyota Corollas

00:58:26.010 --> 00:58:27.650
and do their cleaning services,

00:58:27.650 --> 00:58:29.100
but it's all Bolivian.

00:58:29.100 --> 00:58:31.150
Occasionally they'll let in an outsider,

00:58:31.150 --> 00:58:33.348
say a Peruvian or Guatemalan,

00:58:33.348 --> 00:58:36.130
but it's very interesting how the ethnic,

00:58:36.130 --> 00:58:38.080
you know, there is, you know,

00:58:38.080 --> 00:58:40.860
as people stay and integrate,

00:58:40.860 --> 00:58:44.470
or certainly, by the second
generation or young children,

00:58:44.470 --> 00:58:46.360
there's probably a lot
more crossing the lines.

00:58:46.360 --> 00:58:48.130
But I think when you first arrive,

00:58:48.130 --> 00:58:51.100
there's a real tendency
to stick with your own.

00:58:52.280 --> 00:58:53.113
Yes.

00:58:54.023 --> 00:58:55.300
- [Audience Member 4] Thanks a lot, Marie,

00:58:55.300 --> 00:58:58.920
for bringing us some geographic
concepts to migration

00:58:58.920 --> 00:59:01.482
that we don't get enough of, I think.

00:59:01.482 --> 00:59:03.790
Couple of questions. One is,

00:59:03.790 --> 00:59:04.800
could you tell us a little bit

00:59:04.800 --> 00:59:07.210
about when migration kicks off

00:59:07.210 --> 00:59:08.460
from the Valle Alto?

00:59:09.530 --> 00:59:12.100
What period, what kicks it off?

00:59:12.100 --> 00:59:14.190
And then as far as the connections

00:59:14.190 --> 00:59:16.370
to the Washington DC area,

00:59:16.370 --> 00:59:19.170
what is, what draws the pioneers there?

00:59:19.170 --> 00:59:23.240
What is the initial hook there? Thanks.

00:59:23.240 --> 00:59:24.073
- [Marie] Great.

00:59:26.030 --> 00:59:28.790
So people in the Valle
Alto started migrating

00:59:28.790 --> 00:59:32.720
in the 20s, but they weren't
going to North America.

00:59:33.717 --> 00:59:37.740
An early movement to Chile
and then also Argentina.

00:59:37.740 --> 00:59:39.400
That was clearly the big destination

00:59:39.400 --> 00:59:40.980
and it would be much more,

00:59:40.980 --> 00:59:43.470
a bus ride to Argentina,
kind of a long bus ride,

00:59:43.470 --> 00:59:44.960
and coming back and forth.

00:59:44.960 --> 00:59:46.570
Maybe staying there for several years

00:59:46.570 --> 00:59:50.660
and then coming back.

00:59:51.710 --> 00:59:53.810
I've met some people that
literally call themselves

00:59:53.810 --> 00:59:56.340
pioneers that went to the US.

00:59:56.340 --> 01:00:00.610
And these first pioneers
came in the 1960s,

01:00:00.610 --> 01:00:02.660
late 60s, early 70s,

01:00:02.660 --> 01:00:05.630
one of them came as a young woman,

01:00:05.630 --> 01:00:07.290
worked as a domestic,

01:00:07.290 --> 01:00:09.970
eventually got a college degree,

01:00:09.970 --> 01:00:11.470
her daughter went to Harvard,

01:00:11.470 --> 01:00:15.320
and now is the only elected
Bolivian official in the US.

01:00:15.320 --> 01:00:19.300
She was elected by the
Arlington County school board.

01:00:19.300 --> 01:00:21.380
Emma Violand-Sanchez.

01:00:21.380 --> 01:00:24.080
And she tells this, you know,

01:00:24.080 --> 01:00:27.240
the rags to riches story
that will just make you cry.

01:00:27.240 --> 01:00:29.850
She is a believer in what can happen,

01:00:29.850 --> 01:00:34.640
these transformations and
opportunities that happen.

01:00:34.640 --> 01:00:37.330
But most of the Bolivians
really started coming

01:00:37.330 --> 01:00:41.180
in the early 80s and
Bolivia was in terrible

01:00:41.180 --> 01:00:44.330
economic free fall, hyper inflation.

01:00:44.330 --> 01:00:47.210
And then Argentina wasn't
looking so good either.

01:00:47.210 --> 01:00:49.490
So this notion of,

01:00:49.490 --> 01:00:51.130
we'd better try someplace new,

01:00:51.130 --> 01:00:52.330
somebody knew somebody,

01:00:52.330 --> 01:00:55.000
and then the classic
kind of chain migration.

01:00:55.000 --> 01:00:59.670
Then very clearly, even before 9/11,

01:00:59.670 --> 01:01:02.960
when Operation Gatekeeper
went in in '96, '97,

01:01:02.960 --> 01:01:04.510
it got a lot harder,

01:01:04.510 --> 01:01:06.980
because many people from the Valle Alto,

01:01:06.980 --> 01:01:08.350
they just look at where they're from,

01:01:08.350 --> 01:01:10.410
and they're never given a visa.

01:01:10.410 --> 01:01:12.240
They just assume they're
intended migrants,

01:01:12.240 --> 01:01:15.060
so then they will often come illegally.

01:01:15.060 --> 01:01:16.800
And it's very expensive.

01:01:16.800 --> 01:01:19.320
$15000, it's a lot of money.

01:01:20.400 --> 01:01:22.250
You've gotta work that debt off.

01:01:22.250 --> 01:01:24.820
So then the promised land became Spain,

01:01:24.820 --> 01:01:29.110
and there are twice as
many Bolivians in Spain now

01:01:29.110 --> 01:01:30.540
than in the United States.

01:01:31.610 --> 01:01:34.970
And they really poured into
Spain for several years.

01:01:34.970 --> 01:01:37.030
And then a few other places.

01:01:37.030 --> 01:01:39.960
Italy's got quite a few,
so what's interesting,

01:01:39.960 --> 01:01:43.510
you know, unlike the
Mexican immigration story,

01:01:43.510 --> 01:01:45.900
it's overwhelmingly to the US,

01:01:45.900 --> 01:01:49.130
what is it, 96, 97% of
Mexicans who emigrate

01:01:49.130 --> 01:01:49.963
come to the US.

01:01:50.910 --> 01:01:52.850
Bolivia's obviously much smaller,

01:01:52.850 --> 01:01:55.590
proportionally it has a
very large emigrant stream,

01:01:55.590 --> 01:01:58.580
but they've always gone
to a variety of places.

01:01:58.580 --> 01:02:00.430
Both within South America and Europe.

01:02:00.430 --> 01:02:03.790
There's even an interesting flow to Japan

01:02:03.790 --> 01:02:07.890
because Bolivia received
something like 100 Japanese,

01:02:07.890 --> 01:02:10.310
you know, when the Brazilian,

01:02:10.310 --> 01:02:11.480
mostly they were going to Brazil,

01:02:11.480 --> 01:02:14.920
and then if you could
somehow prove ancestry,

01:02:14.920 --> 01:02:16.710
you can get to Japan.

01:02:16.710 --> 01:02:18.820
So the embassy estimates there's

01:02:18.820 --> 01:02:22.120
like 2000 Bolivian Japanese,

01:02:22.120 --> 01:02:25.370
we say that with
quotation marks, in Japan,

01:02:25.370 --> 01:02:28.220
because they're probably
not ethnically Japanese

01:02:28.220 --> 01:02:30.290
but they somehow proved that.

01:02:31.460 --> 01:02:35.280
So that strategy, and I think right now,

01:02:35.280 --> 01:02:37.090
there's, the flows are not,

01:02:38.160 --> 01:02:39.810
illegal flows are very small,

01:02:41.150 --> 01:02:43.080
because it's so hard and expensive.

01:02:43.080 --> 01:02:46.290
And there's also been a pretty
significant deportation.

01:02:48.320 --> 01:02:50.180
I was looking at some statistics

01:02:50.180 --> 01:02:54.690
and the Obama administration has deported

01:02:54.690 --> 01:02:57.090
more people than any other President,

01:02:57.930 --> 01:02:59.790
any other presidential administration,

01:02:59.790 --> 01:03:01.460
still got another year to go.

01:03:01.460 --> 01:03:03.540
I don't think that was
totally intentional.

01:03:03.540 --> 01:03:07.740
It was about the changes
in secure communities

01:03:07.740 --> 01:03:10.120
but we're not just talking
stopping people at the borders,

01:03:10.120 --> 01:03:13.410
these are deportations of people
who've lived several years.

01:03:13.410 --> 01:03:15.140
And it's wrenching.

01:03:15.140 --> 01:03:16.870
I've been to fundraisers when

01:03:18.000 --> 01:03:19.950
you know, basically what happens,

01:03:19.950 --> 01:03:22.130
dad drives to work, dad gets stopped,

01:03:22.130 --> 01:03:24.220
dad doesn't have a driver's license

01:03:24.220 --> 01:03:26.710
because you can't get one
if you're undocumented.

01:03:26.710 --> 01:03:27.640
Dad is arrested.

01:03:28.570 --> 01:03:30.580
Dad's detained for months

01:03:30.580 --> 01:03:31.910
and the family's stuck.

01:03:33.270 --> 01:03:34.450
Kids might be Americans

01:03:34.450 --> 01:03:39.350
so that deportation story is obviously

01:03:39.350 --> 01:03:41.600
a kind of a national deflection strategy.

01:03:42.730 --> 01:03:47.510
But it's plays out all the
time in the Latino media.

01:03:47.510 --> 01:03:50.520
We don't hear it as
much in the Anglo media.

01:03:50.520 --> 01:03:54.240
But estimates are that one
in four Latinos in the US

01:03:55.440 --> 01:03:59.110
know someone who has
been deported or will be.

01:04:00.220 --> 01:04:04.090
And that's a really sad figure but it's,

01:04:04.090 --> 01:04:06.220
it plays up at least in the work

01:04:06.220 --> 01:04:07.200
I've been doing in Washington,

01:04:07.200 --> 01:04:09.870
how immigrants perceive
their opportunities.

01:04:09.870 --> 01:04:12.265
I think it merely means
the economic challenges

01:04:12.265 --> 01:04:14.900
with the recession is just,

01:04:14.900 --> 01:04:16.600
coming here is not so appealing.

01:04:18.370 --> 01:04:19.203
Greg?

01:04:20.740 --> 01:04:21.950
Use the microphone.

01:04:21.950 --> 01:04:23.250
(audience member mumbles)

01:04:23.250 --> 01:04:25.031
This is also my brother.

01:04:25.031 --> 01:04:25.864
(audience laughs)

01:04:25.864 --> 01:04:26.900
- [Marie's Brother] So I was looking

01:04:26.900 --> 01:04:29.670
at the economic examples,

01:04:29.670 --> 01:04:32.450
the economic examples from
Prince William County,

01:04:32.450 --> 01:04:33.283
two questions.

01:04:33.283 --> 01:04:37.107
How well known in that
community were those

01:04:37.107 --> 01:04:40.490
in the economic consequences
of the immigration policy.

01:04:40.490 --> 01:04:43.120
And looking at what's happening in Alabama

01:04:43.120 --> 01:04:45.220
and earlier in Arizona,

01:04:45.220 --> 01:04:49.069
what could our elected officials
learn from geographers?

01:04:49.069 --> 01:04:49.902
- [Marie] Hmm.

01:04:49.902 --> 01:04:51.300
(audience laughs)

01:04:51.300 --> 01:04:53.017
Thank you for that policy question.

01:04:53.017 --> 01:04:54.420
(audience laughs)

01:04:54.420 --> 01:04:57.600
So in Prince William County,

01:04:57.600 --> 01:04:59.460
and as people have looked at the data,

01:04:59.460 --> 01:05:03.300
it's very hard to tease out
the impacts of the recession,

01:05:03.300 --> 01:05:06.930
which was coming on at the same time.

01:05:06.930 --> 01:05:10.740
But and there was also a lot
of home foreclosures there,

01:05:10.740 --> 01:05:12.390
especially among Hispanics,

01:05:12.390 --> 01:05:15.570
and was that because they
just decided to walk away

01:05:15.570 --> 01:05:17.200
because of the political environment?

01:05:17.200 --> 01:05:19.300
The political environment was really ugly.

01:05:21.352 --> 01:05:22.710
And I went to a couple meetings

01:05:22.710 --> 01:05:24.420
and it was terrifying.

01:05:24.420 --> 01:05:27.970
It really had this mob quality of people

01:05:27.970 --> 01:05:29.964
just inciting, saying outrageous things,

01:05:29.964 --> 01:05:31.230
from both sides.

01:05:32.790 --> 01:05:35.830
So one of the things
that I learned from that.

01:05:35.830 --> 01:05:37.580
I went and interviewed the sheriff,

01:05:37.580 --> 01:05:39.220
who had to enforce those.

01:05:39.220 --> 01:05:40.840
And I asked him, you know,

01:05:41.780 --> 01:05:44.570
let's say, tomorrow
legislation was changed

01:05:44.570 --> 01:05:46.740
and everybody that came undocumented,

01:05:46.740 --> 01:05:49.650
which was the target of
their search, became legal,

01:05:49.650 --> 01:05:51.310
what would that mean to you?

01:05:51.310 --> 01:05:53.890
And he said, it would make
my life so much easier.

01:05:53.890 --> 01:05:56.170
This is a really hard thing to do.

01:05:56.170 --> 01:05:57.630
We can't police this way.

01:05:59.390 --> 01:06:02.150
And to me, the lesson from Prince Williams

01:06:02.150 --> 01:06:04.520
was that it, again it often happens,

01:06:04.520 --> 01:06:06.620
it was really one or two politicians

01:06:06.620 --> 01:06:09.240
that saw an opportunity to play on fears

01:06:09.240 --> 01:06:10.790
and prejudices and run with it.

01:06:11.840 --> 01:06:13.900
So that is one lesson.

01:06:13.900 --> 01:06:17.250
In terms of Alabama, I don't get it.

01:06:17.250 --> 01:06:20.140
It's not like Alabama has a lot
of immigrants to begin with,

01:06:20.140 --> 01:06:25.140
but I do think it plays
upon a general feeling

01:06:25.140 --> 01:06:29.460
of all immigration is somehow
tainted with illegality now

01:06:29.460 --> 01:06:32.340
because of the, the deadlock we're in.

01:06:32.340 --> 01:06:33.560
You know, there has been,

01:06:33.560 --> 01:06:35.580
people have been saying
immigration reform is coming,

01:06:35.580 --> 01:06:36.620
it's coming, it's coming,

01:06:36.620 --> 01:06:37.550
it's not coming.

01:06:38.540 --> 01:06:41.500
And so, states and jurisdictions think,

01:06:41.500 --> 01:06:43.152
well, this is the way we act,

01:06:43.152 --> 01:06:48.152
and I'm not sure Alabama can
go much lower economically,

01:06:49.110 --> 01:06:53.690
so that's you know, hard to
really, you know, compete.

01:06:53.690 --> 01:06:56.990
But Arizona, I think there is some pretty

01:06:56.990 --> 01:07:00.130
convincing evidence that it's
having economic implications

01:07:00.130 --> 01:07:02.500
but at the same time,

01:07:02.500 --> 01:07:04.960
you know, if you really
believe that immigration

01:07:04.960 --> 01:07:08.230
is making your place worse,

01:07:08.230 --> 01:07:10.370
then you're gonna need to martial evidence

01:07:10.370 --> 01:07:13.090
that will support that, and people do.

01:07:16.439 --> 01:07:17.272
- [Emcee] I think that was probably,

01:07:17.272 --> 01:07:18.780
unless somebody has
another burning question,

01:07:18.780 --> 01:07:21.280
it's probably the last question,

01:07:21.280 --> 01:07:24.380
what can geographers offer
to politics in a good way,

01:07:24.380 --> 01:07:26.840
for us to all reflect on,

01:07:26.840 --> 01:07:29.580
and also think about the ways in which

01:07:29.580 --> 01:07:32.210
Marie has so creatively used some of these

01:07:32.210 --> 01:07:34.690
Sauerian concepts to engage us

01:07:34.690 --> 01:07:37.000
in something of everyday concern.

01:07:37.000 --> 01:07:38.640
We thank you enormously.

01:07:38.640 --> 01:07:42.460
Please join us for refreshments
just in the atrium here,

01:07:42.460 --> 01:07:44.244
and thanks again, Marie.

01:07:44.244 --> 01:07:45.777
(audience applauds)
- [Marie] Thank you.

